@flexiarg war-machine/ambient-pattern-retrieval
@title Ambient Pattern Retrieval

! conclusion: A library of reusable strategies that is searched automatically on every conversation turn functions as ambient intelligence - the system's background awareness of what it knows, surfaced without being asked.

  + CONTEXT:
    futon3a's pattern library is searched via MiniLM embeddings on every A->B turn in the REPL, and the results appear as desktop notifications with evidence certificates. The operator does not request the search; it happens as a side-effect of working. Over time, the activation pattern across the library reveals which strategies are repeatedly relevant and which are never activated.

  + IF:
    The system can search a large pattern library automatically on each work turn and surface the results ambiently rather than as an interruption.

  + HOWEVER:
    A large knowledge base is only useful when the right pieces surface at the right time. Retrieval quality depends on embedding quality and library coverage, and notification fatigue will turn ambient retrieval into noise if low-relevance patterns keep firing.

  + THEN:
    Search the library on every turn as a background process. Display results as ambient notifications, log the activation history as evidence, and use the resulting hot-zone / cold-zone pattern to tune retrieval and train later pre-hoc prediction.

  + BECAUSE:
    Expert practitioners develop intuitions that surface relevant knowledge without deliberate recall. Ambient retrieval externalises that intuition: the system maintains a background awareness of its own knowledge and surfaces relevant pieces as the situation evolves.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Use the activation history to tune retrieval quality and distinguish genuine hot zones from cold library regions that never become relevant.]
